In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the rate of participation.
In that sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike what happens in Canada, the United States is responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line, a majority of American governments have enacted new laws that made it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has been extended since the November 2010 elections, which saw an increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced during 2011 restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to an American citizenship test.
On the other hand, these laws reduce the pre-emptive voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the election and withdraw the right to vote to citizens with criminal backgrounds.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present an identity document with photographs.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indian law in 2008.
The Republican authorities therefore rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bill projects in 34 states to force voters to present an identity document with photography.
It is important to note that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a document of universal identity, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people aged to vote, do not have any identity document with photographs issued by a government agency of their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
However, obtaining the required identity document often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions therefore disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of those who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have an identity document with photographs.
And there's more.
In many states students, voters who vote the most for democratic candidates, cannot use the identity document with photographs issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states authorise members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote to the Republican parties to use the documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required the proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present this requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Spanish vote.
It seems that two out of three Spanish voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported certain laws in 2011 that abolished electoral registration on the same day of election in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create an aid service for voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, electoral registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared with 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators passed laws in five other states that favoured the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13 per cent of the state voters.
In the case of the Hispanics, exactly the same would happen.
These represent only 11 per cent of the voters, which is equal to 24 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the register of voters.
In this regard, democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Prosecutor's Ministry intervenes to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, it was possible to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 States adopted the law requiring the submission of an identity document with photographs.
However, it is unmistakable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the party's nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they intend to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
