With bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time depositaries of accounting books, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing the anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key hit consists of writing that new transaction in that book.
This is due to the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched by computers and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that supplementary line.
This is a phase of file-sharing, i.e., the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical trail.
Computers "cogen" the new transaction and add a number before "crossing" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular trail (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is good.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any change would change the mark.
If, in order to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphan, as both have different marks.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, most likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the computational power.
